\section{System Integration: From Frequency and Variance to State Estimation}
\label{sec:integration}

\paragraph{Coupling logic.}
The frequency tracker (\S\ref{sec:freq-trackers}) and the variance-aware tuner (\S\ref{sec:adaptation}) act as an exogenous supervisor for the multiplicative EKF on \(\mathrm{SO}(3)\times\mathbb{R}^{12}\).
At each IMU step, the stack computes (i) the smoothed dominant acceleration frequency \(\widehat{f}(t)\) and phase \(\widehat{\phi}(t)\), and (ii) the debiased vertical specific-force variance \(\widehat{\sigma}_a^2(t)\).
These feed the adaptive law \eqref{eq:rs-law} to set the target pseudo-measurement covariance \(R_S^\star(t)\), with mild anisotropy to reflect horizontal coupling.
Joseph-form updates ensure numerical symmetry/PSD, magnetometer updates are gated to stabilize yaw observability after the initial transient, and the direction subfilter in \S\ref{sec:direction} consumes \(\widehat{\phi}(t)\) directly to phase-gate horizontal information.

\paragraph{Identifiability and failure modes.}
The design emphasizes \emph{phase coherence} over pointwise spectral accuracy: since \(\widehat{f}(t)\) is extracted from the forcing channel \(a_z\), the filter retains observability even when displacement spectra are multicomponent.
Pathological regimes include (a) extremely low SNR where zero-crossing fallback dominates, (b) near-commensurate dual lines causing slow tracker beating, and (c) abrupt sea-state transitions that temporarily bias \(\widehat{\sigma}_a\).
All three are mitigated by bounded gains, clamping of \(\tau,\sigma_a,R_S\), and slow application of targets.

\paragraph{Scientific stance.}
The overarching idea is to \emph{measure what the ocean gives us} in acceleration—period and vertical energy—and translate it into the \emph{minimum regularization} that keeps integral states anchored without dulling swell response. This preserves the physics signal while preventing drift that would otherwise arise from integrating latent acceleration.

