\section{Experimental Results}
\label{sec:results}

\subsection{Setup}
We use the synthetic dataset and metrics of \S\ref{sec:sim-and-eval}:
four sea states (W1–W4) across five wave models (Gerstner, JONSWAP, PM-Stokes, Fenton, Cnoidal); each run is \SI{20}{min} at \SI{240}{Hz}, with body-frame IMU and world-frame reference.
Performance is reported over the terminal \SI{60}{s} (steady-state).

\subsection{Displacement and Attitude Accuracy}
Table~\ref{tab:acc} summarizes per-axis RMS and RMS\%Hs; Table~\ref{tab:attn-tuner} reports roll/pitch/yaw RMS and tuner telemetry (\(\widehat{f}\), applied \(\tau,\sigma_a,R_S\) and targets).
Across single-component nonlinear waves (Gerstner, Fenton, Cnoidal), vertical accuracy remains well within engineering gates, with bounded horizontal drift despite significant attitude motion.
In directional seas (JONSWAP, PM-Stokes), accuracy degrades gracefully with increasing \(H_s\) and \(T_p\); the adaptive law raises \(R_S\) with \(\tau^3\) as intended, maintaining phase coherence while limiting low-frequency bias.

\subsection{Frequency-Tracker Comparison}
\label{subsec:tracker-comp}
We compare three policies (Aranovskiy, KalmANF, Schmitt) as front-ends to the same unifier (smoothing horizon \(T_f\)).
Evaluation uses (i) frequency RMSE against the simulator’s dominant line of \(a_z\), (ii) phase-slip rate relative to the reference phase, and (iii) downstream effect on displacement RMS.
Aranovskiy exhibits lowest latency and strong phase fidelity at modest SNR; KalmANF yields the cleanest steady estimates under noise with slightly higher agility cost; Schmitt provides a robust safety net with quantized behavior.
Crucially, once passed through the unifier, downstream displacement differences are second-order except in rapidly time-varying seas, where KalmANF’s larger \(Q\) improves tracking at the expense of small jitter.

\subsection{Adaptive Tuning Dynamics}
\label{subsec:tuning-dyn}
Figure~\ref{fig:tuner-dyn} overlays \(\widehat{f}(t)\), \(\widehat{\sigma}_a(t)\), and the applied/target \((\tau,\sigma_a,R_S)\) during representative W2–W4 runs.
We observe (1) convergence of \(R_S\) to the \(\sigma_a\tau^3\) target, (2) anisotropic stabilization of the integral channel that prevents slow drift, and (3) negligible impact on swell-band amplitude.
Mis-tracking episodes in \(\widehat{\sigma}_a\) correlate with transient vertical RMS excursions, underscoring the centrality of variance estimation.

\subsection{Wave Direction: Angle and Signed Propagation}
\label{subsec:dir-results}
The direction module (\S\ref{sec:direction}) is evaluated with four measures:
(i) median absolute angular error \(\mathrm{MAE}_{180}\) modulo \(180^\circ\),
(ii) signed angular error \(\mathrm{MAE}_{\pm}\) using the simulator’s propagation sign,
(iii) flip rate (fraction of frames where the signed direction changes), and
(iv) \(95\%\) uncertainty coverage based on \eqref{eq:angle-unc}.
Results show sub-\(10^\circ\) \(\mathrm{MAE}_{180}\) in W1–W3 and controlled degradation in W4; the signed detector exhibits low flip rates once magnetometer gating stabilizes yaw.
Coverage closely matches nominal, validating the tangent-space uncertainty projection.

\subsection{Ablations and Stressors}
\label{subsec:ablations}
We report three controlled ablations:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{No adaptation} (\(R_S\) fixed): vertical RMS grows with \(T_p\), confirming the need for \(\tau^3\) scaling.
  \item \textbf{No unifier} (raw tracker output): increased chattering in \(\tau,\ R_S\) and worsened displacement RMS under multi-component interference.
  \item \textbf{No phase blackout} in direction KF: loss of angular stability near quadrature and inflated uncertainty.
\end{enumerate}
These isolates demonstrate that each ingredient targets a distinct failure mode.

\subsection{Limitations}
\label{subsec:limits}
The approach inherits three limitations: reliance on a dominant narrowband in \(a_z\), sensitivity of \(\widehat{\sigma}_a\) to abrupt transients, and reduced signed-direction reliability under extreme yaw drift if magnetometer updates are unavailable.
We mitigate but do not eliminate these effects with smoothing, clamping, and gating.

